com.analog.lyric.collect

Class KeyedPriorityQueue<K,E extends IKeyed<K>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • com.analog.lyric.collect.AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<K,E>
          • com.analog.lyric.collect.KeyedPriorityQueue<K,E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Queue<E>

    @NotThreadSafe
@NonNullByDefault(value=false)
public class KeyedPriorityQueue<K,E extends IKeyed<K>>
extends AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue<K,E>
implements java.io.Serializable
    A priority queue that works on elements that have inherent keys and that does not allow more than one entry with the same key.

    This is similar to PriorityQueue except that:

    • Elements must implement the IKeyed interface.
    • Methods containsKey(Object) and removeKey(Object) provide key-based methods for manipulating the queue.
    • Calls to AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue.offer(Object) and AbstractKeyedPriorityQueue.add(Object) will return false when an element with the same key is already in the queue.
    • Calls to contains(Object) are O(1) instead of O(n).
    • When two elements have the same priority, the first element added will be returned by AbstractQueue.remove() et al.
    Since:
    0.05
    See Also:
    UniquePriorityQueue, Serialized Form

      • KeyedPriorityQueue

        public KeyedPriorityQueue(int initialCapacity,
                  @Nullable
                  java.util.Comparator<? super E> priorityComparator)
        Constructs empty queue.
        Parameters:
        initialCapacity - provides a hint as to the intended size of the queue.
        priorityComparator - defines the priority ordering among elements. If null, then natural ordering will be used and all elements must implement Comparable and must be comparable to existing elements in the queue.

      • KeyedPriorityQueue

        public KeyedPriorityQueue(@NonNull
                  java.util.Collection<? extends E> collection)
        Constructs queue with elements from collection.
        Parameters:
        collection - specifies the elements to add to the queue which will be added in the same order as the collection's iterator. If the collection is a SortedSet, then its comparator will be used to determine priorities. Otherwise the natural order will be used (see KeyedPriorityQueue(int, Comparator)).
